            "author_association": "MEMBER",
            "body": "> Build should not break unexpectedly because GitHub changed their tarball generation strategy in the future.\r\n\r\nMeh. From end user perspective this is a non-issue. Github changes tarball strategy -> neovim doesn't work for an hour -> we update SHA's -> everyone lives happily ever after. We're not saving lives here and don't require 99.999% uptime, so I'd consider this a non-problem.\r\n\r\nWhat is problematic with this though is that bisecting might break in the future, which I think is a much more relevant and realistic problem. It's not really something users need to worry about, but it is definitely something we need to worry about. I'm unsure if this problem is tracked somewhere else, so I'll let this issue open for the time being (although this could use a real dedicated problem statement instead of me just latching onto this issue). We could switch from checking the tarball SHA to instead rely on the the commit SHA instead. @justinmk @bfredl @jamessan thoughts?",
