            "author_association": "NONE",
            "body": "> I am sorry, but is this an actual problem, or just a hypothetical? There have been literally dozens of people downloading and building these successfully without any reports of problems.\r\n\r\nIt is practical in the sense that this has happened in the past (iirc even multiple times) and many projects were broken. I would not expect this to happen very often in the future, but it is still a possibility.\r\nSo I don't think this is urgent to be addressed immediately but certainly something one must be at least aware of.\r\n\r\n> From end user perspective this is a non-issue. Github changes tarball strategy -> neovim doesn't work for an hour -> we update SHA's -> everyone lives happily ever after. We're not saving lives here and don't require 99.999% uptime, so I'd consider this a non-problem.\r\n\r\nThis is true for the HEAD of development, but as you mentioned it is not for previous commits and especially not for any previously released version. Even if a new version is released, older release tags/tarballs, which are integrated in distributions or used by users holding back updates because of breaking changes, will still be broken.\r\n\r\n> We could switch from checking the tarball SHA to instead rely on the the commit SHA instead.\r\n\r\nThis only works if you clone dependencies directly with git, which could be inconvenient. If on the other hand you download a tarball from e.g. https://github.com/libuv/libuv/archive/541329d51f82bce83bd81ff7640edabfc32d149c.tar.gz, you lose the entire security benefit of checking the hashes in case e.g. the user sits behind a proxy that alters the download, and they have its root ca cert installed.",
