            "author_association": "MEMBER",
            "body": "> If on the other hand you download a tarball from e.g.Â https://github.com/libuv/libuv/archive/541329d51f82bce83bd81ff7640edabfc32d149c.tar.gz, you lose the entire security benefit of checking the hashes in case e.g. the user sits behind a proxy that alters the download, and they have its root ca cert installed.\n\nWait, I don't follow. I'm pretty sure cmake checks the SHA of the downloaded tarball locally, so I don't think this should be a problem. I assume you mean this could be a problem if we rely on the git hash instead? If we go with the git hash route then cmake won't download the tarball of the hash, it will clone the git repo and locally check out the commit. Unsure if this is more secure or not, I'm not a security expert. To me this seems like this attack might just as likely occur when git cloning a repo.\n\nHonestly, this is a high ask. Are there any other FOSS projects (except maybe nix?) that is prepared for the complete collapse of society? Is this a problem most projects have attempted to solve, and if so, how have they achieved it?",
